'''Tyler Beckham Thigpen''' (born April 14, 1984 in [[Winnsboro, South Carolina]])<ref name="Thigpen"/><ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/> is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] of the [[National Football League]]. Thigpen was drafted out of [[Coastal Carolina University]] in the seventh round of the [[2007 NFL Draft]] (217th overall) by the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. Thigpen is the current starting quarterback for the Chiefs.<ref name="Thigpen">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen | publisher=Pro Football Reference | url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/ThigTy00.htm | accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref><ref name="Spread changes"/>

Thigpen was the first quarterback to play for the [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football]] team.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen - Coastal Carolina"/> He led the Chanticleers program to a 30-8 record as starting quarterback.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/><ref name="Chiefs have own"/> Thigpen holds the single-season and career passing records in every major statistical category at Coastal Carolina.<ref name="Football alum"/>

Thigpen entered the [[2008 Kansas City Chiefs season]] as the third-string quarterback, but emerged as the starter following season-ending injuries to [[Brodie Croyle]] and [[Damon Huard]].<ref name="A Different Kind"/><ref name="unheralded"/><ref name="Croyle sprains"/> The Chiefs subsequently altered their offensive gameplan to a [[spread offense]] to help Thigpen and the rest of the young Chiefs team to play to the best of their abilities.<ref name="Spread changes"/><ref name="Breaking the Mold"/> Whether or not Thigpen develops into the franchise quarterback the Chiefs were counting on Croyle to become, barring injury, his presence in the Chiefs' revamped offense will remain through the 2008 season.<ref name="Breaking the Mold"/>

==Early years and collegiate career==
Thigpen attended [[Fairfield Central High School]] in [[Winnsboro, South Carolina]] and became an All-South Carolina selection as a senior [[running back]].<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/> Thigpen also played [[wide receiver]] and [[Punter (American football)|punter]] in high school.<ref name="Coastal inks">{{cite web | title=Coastal inks 13 football recruits | url=http://www.goccusports.com/football/?news=3514 | publisher=Coastal Carolina University Athletics | date=2002-02-06 | accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref> In February 2002, he elected to go to [[Coastal Carolina University]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]],<ref name="Coastal inks"/> and majored in sports management.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/>

Thigpen was the first quarterback in Coastal Carolina history, and wore the jersey number 16.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen - Coastal Carolina"/> The Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football program began in 2003.<ref name="StarTrib">{{cite web|title=Vikings sign quarterback Thigpen|url=http://www.startribune.com/510/story/1193044.html|date=[[2007-05-18]]|publisher=''[[Star Tribune]]''|accessdate=2007-05-19}}</ref> The team competes in the [[Big South Conference]] of the [[NCAA Football Championship Subdivision#Football_Championship Subdivision|NCAA Football Championship Subdivision]].

Thigpen had a 30-8 record in four seasons (41 games and 39 starts).<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/><ref name="Chiefs have own"/> Under his leadership, the Chanticleers had a 34-11 record in his four seasons with the team.<ref name="Football alum">{{cite web | title=Football alum Thigpen to make first NFL start Sunday | url=http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4800&ATCLID=1584601 | author=Coastal Carolina University Athletics | publisher=Big South Conference | date=2008-09-18 | accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref> In four of those seasons, the team finished with 9 victories.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen - Coastal Carolina"/> After the Chanticleers' inaugural season in which the team finished with a 6-5 record, Thigpen led the team to a 10-1 record in 2004.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen - Coastal Carolina">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen - Coastal Carolina | url=http://rivals.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/players/104363 | publisher=Rivals.com | accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref> He was named [[Big South Conference]] Player of the Year in 2006, when he completed 217-of-339 passes for 3,296 yards and 29 touchdowns, and carried 113 times for 656 yards and five touchdowns.<ref name="StarTrib"/> Thigpen was also the first Chanticleer to be chosen a consensus [[All-American]].<ref name=Chiefs to start Tyler">{{cite web | title=Chiefs to start Tyler Thigpen at QB | url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/chiefs/2008-09-17-thigpen-start_N.htm | author=Associated Press | work=[[USA Today]] | date=2008-09-17 | accessdate=2008-12-11}}</ref>

He played alongside wide receiver [[Jerome Simpson]], now with the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], and running back [[Mike Tolbert]], now with the [[San Diego Chargers]], to help lead the young Chanticleers program to major victories against #1 [[James Madison University|James Madison]] in [[2005]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Football shocks #1 James Madison 31&ndash;27 | url=http://www.goccusports.com/football/?news=932 | publisher=Coastal Carolina University Athletics | date=2005-09-10 | accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref> and # 3 [[Furman University|Furman]] in [[2006]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Football upsets #3 Furman 29&ndash;27 | url=http://www.goccusports.com/football/?news=2343 | publisher=Coastal Carolina University Athletics | date=2006-10-07 | accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref> He led the Chanticleers to the NCAA Division I-AA playoffs and a Big South Conference championship.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/> Thigpen holds the single-season and career passing records in every major statistical category at Coastal Carolina.<ref name="Football alum"/><ref>{{cite web| title= Tyler Thigpen Biography| url=http://www.goccusports.com/football/?player=828 |publisher= Coastal Carolina University Athletics | accessdate= 2007-05-04}}</ref>

==NFL career==
===2007 NFL Draft===
Tyler Thigpen was selected in the seventh round of the [[2007 NFL Draft]] by the [[Minnesota Vikings]], becoming the first player in Coastal Carolina and Big South Conference history to be drafted in the NFL.<ref name="Tyler Thigpen biography"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Football's Thigpen to Be Featured on ESPN|url=http://www.goccusports.com/football/?news=3397&season=109|publisher=Coastal Carolina University Athletics|accessdate=2007-05-19}}</ref>

Going into the 2007 NFL Draft, the Chiefs had Thigpen on their list of players that they had considering selecting in the later rounds, possibly with their seventh round selection (#231).<ref name="A Different Kind">{{cite web | title=A Different Kind of Homecoming | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/07/31/a_different_kind_of_homecoming/ | last=Gretz | first=Bob | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | date=2008-07-31 | accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref> As the draft played out, the Vikings chose Thigpen with the 217th choice.<ref name="A Different Kind"/>

